body:
I encountered an unexpected behavior from the borrow checker. Being unable to determine if this is a bug or an intended behavior I post it here for every one to see.

I tried this code:

```rust
struct S {
	v : Vec<usize>
}

impl S {

	fn fst_mut(&mut self) -> &usize {
		&self.v[0]
	}

	fn fst(&self) -> &usize {
		&self.v[0]
	}
}

fn main() {
	let mut structure = S { v : vec![0] };
	let info = structure.fst_mut();
	let _ = structure.fst();
	let i = *info;
}
```

I expected to see this happen: Accepted by borrow checker

Instead, it was rejected by borrow checker with error :

```
error[E0502]: cannot borrow `structure` as immutable because it is also borrowed as mutable
  --> test_rustc.rs:20:10
   |
18 |     let info = structure.fst_mut();
   |                ------------------- mutable borrow occurs here
19 |
20 |     let _ = structure.fst();
   |             ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ immutable borrow occurs here
21 |     let i = *info;
   |             ----- mutable borrow later used here

error: aborting due to previous error; 1 warning emitted
```

The reason of this compilation failure is that the borrow checker considers `info` as a mutable borrow to `structure` however it's type is `&usize`.


`rustc --version --verbose`:
```
rustc 1.67.0-nightly (b7bc90fea 2022-11-21)
binary: rustc
commit-hash: b7bc90fea3b441234a84b49fdafeb75815eebbab
commit-date: 2022-11-21
host: x86_64-apple-darwin
release: 1.67.0-nightly
LLVM version: 15.0.4
```
